1 Peak Velocity

1.1 Effect of Probability

Peak Velocity WAS NOT significantly affected by probability of reward (p = 1.566e-01, slope = 2.360e-03). This was tested with an LMER with main outcome of probability and random effect of subject.

Table 1.1: Peak Velocity P-Values for effect of Probability
P-Value Slope Intercept
All Target LMER 1.566e-01 2.360e-03 1.666e-03 4.667e-01
Target 1/4 LMER 9.901e-01 -2.173e-05 1.754e-03 4.683e-01
Target 1/4 ANOVA 9.993e-01 F val: 8.306e-07

1.1.0.1 Comparison of 0% and 100% Reward

In a paired t test of subject averages, there WAS NOT a significant difference between 0% and 100% reward conditions for Peak Velocity (p = 9.914e-01). .

In a ANOVA test of subject averages, there WAS NOT a significant difference between 0% and 100% reward conditions for Peak Velocity (p = 9.981e-01). .

1.2 Effect of Trial

1.3 Peak Velocity Following Reward

Using a paried t test, across subjects, the Peak Velocity in trials following rewarded trials WAS statistically different than trials following nonrewarded tirlas (p = 8.164e-04)

Using an ANOVA test, across subjects, the Peak Velocity in trials following rewarded trials WAS NOT statistically different than trials following nonrewarded tirlas (p = 8.164e-04)

Table 1.2: Peak Velocity P-Values for effect of Probability
P-Value
T-test 8.164e-04
T-Test Prior==1 3.294e-11
T-Test Prior==0 2.770e-11

In an interacation LMER of probability of reward and prior reward with subject as a random intercept effect, Peak Velocity WAS NOT affected by probability of reward (p = 4.673e-01) and WAS NOT affected by prior reward (p = 1.392e-01). An interaction of the two factors DID affect Peak Velocity (p = 1.066e-02)

Dividing the data set into two groups (trials following reward and trials not following reward) resulted in finding a significant slope of probability (p = 3.937e-03) in trials that follow reward, but finding NO significant slope (p = 4.770e-01) in trials that do not follow reward.

1.3.1 Change in Peak Velocity from previous trial due to Reward

Table 1.4: PeakV Diff Prior P-Values for effect of Probability
P-Value
T-test 3.114e-02
T-Test Prior==1 2.685e-02
T-Test Prior==0 3.750e-02

To further examine this effect of prior reward on Peak Velocity, the change in Peak Velocity was determined from trial to trial. In the above graph Delta Peak Velocity is the difference in Peak Velocity of the current trial minus the previous trial (PV_(trial=n)-PV_(trial=n-1)). There WAS a statistical difference between trials following and not following reward (paired t-test of subject averages, p = 3.114e-02). Peak Velocity WAS significantly different following reward (t-test of subject averages vs a mean of 0, p = 2.685e-02) and Peak Velocity DID significantly different following trials where they were not rewarded (t-test of subject averages vs a mean of 0, p = 3.750e-02).
